Each board member contributed to the statement. Click here to read the statement:

post_text: Last night, Superintendent Chamberlin sent out a message to parents/guardians announcing that all UPSD schools will open fully online on September 8th. This decision was made from the recommendation of the Tacoma-Pierce County Health Department. We know this creates many concerns and challenges for UP families. In the upcoming weeks, we will share additional information about child care opportunities in UP, school schedules, online programming, meal distribution and technology support. To read the full letter sent to families, please click below.

post_text: The University Place School District is excited to announce Rebecca James as the 2019-2020 Teacher of the Year. Rebecca has invested 36 years educating students, 19 of which have been spent teaching special education students in UPSD. She has a tremendous level of experience and knowledge in her field. Rebecca has shared her expertise by supporting her fellow teachers and the paraeducators with whom she works. Congratulations Rebecca, this honor is well deserved!

post_text: University Place School District has always been thankful for the dedicated and caring staff that fill our classrooms. This year, we feel even more grateful as we have watched our staff step up and begin teaching virtually while continuing to engage with their students at a distance. UPSD is lucky to have such a devoted and talented team of teachers working together to serve our students. Teacher Appreciation Week was celebrated a little differently this year, but we hope our teachers felt the love. Thank you UPSD teachers for all that you do to educate, care for, and empower our students!

post_text:
University Place School District Nutrition Services and Transportation departments are teaming up to expand sack lunch meal services during the school shut down beginning March 23, 2020!

Each sack includes lunch and a breakfast for the following day. Students must be present to receive these meals when they are picked up. School buses will be delivering these sack meals to multiple locations throughout the community. To view a list of the drop-off sites, visit the UPSD website at www.upsd83.org.

Grab and go services will continue Monday-Friday at Chambers Primary, Evergreen Primary, Narrows View Intermediate and University Place Primary from 10:30 am -12:30 pm.

post_text: Last week, two restaurants popped up at Curtis High School as a culminating project of the Gourmet Foods class. Much like on the popular TV series, Top Chef, students were divided into two teams to compete in “restaurant wars” as they showcased their knowledge of the restaurant industry. Students learned how to operate the front of house, practice customer service, utilize teamwork, and applied their culinary food preparation and presentation skills in a restaurant setting. Customers “paid” for their meal by completing a review sheet that was totaled and averaged to determine the winner.

post_text: If your family has been impacted by the federal government furlough, your child may qualify for free or reduced-priced meal benefits. The application for these services can be found in Family Access or at www.upsd83.org/departments/nutrition_services. Contact Nutrition Services at 253-566-5700 to learn more about the application process. You can also contact your child’s school counselor for additional resources that may be available to your family.

text:
If your family has been impacted by the federal government furlough, your child may qualify for free or reduced-priced meal benefits. The application for these services can be found in Family Access or at www.upsd83.org/departments/nutrition_services. Contact Nutrition Services at 253-566-5700 to learn more about the application process. You can also contact your child’s school counselor for additional resources that may be available to your family.

UPSD83.ORG
Nutrition Services - University Place School District

post_text: Last week, University Place Primary wrapped up One School, One Book a school wide reading event. This year, UPP read Frindle by Andrew Clements. Every family was provided a copy of the book (thanks to donations from Tacoma Narrows Rotary, University Place Lions Club, and University Place Primary PTSA - UPP PTSA), a reading schedule, a memento from the book, extra reading list, and activity sheets. Guest readers were asked to read sections of the assigned reading during breakfast each morning as an additional opportunity for students to follow along with the story. Thank you to the staff, volunteers, and community for supporting this program!

post_text:
University Place Primary is a Washington State School of Distinction for 2017!

Congratulations to the staff and students at University Place Primary for their selection as a School of Distinction. Schools are selected for this honor based on their ability to improve performance for all students over a five-year period in math and literacy.
